<title type="html"><![CDATA[Real Physics vs. Look-up Table? (plus Demo)]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5163&amp;p=46753#p46753"><![CDATA[
This might be a simple answer and I'm overlooking it, but I am wondering if it is wiser to use real physics on a platformer on the NES, or is using a LUT the best way to go?<br /><br />I've been trying to think of a reason to actually use real physics, because you save a lot of cycles, and an efficient LUT doesn't take that much ROM space.<br /><br />I also created a demo using fixed-point number physics to estimate a falling object. I faked the negative number by using a flag, but there is a constant acceleration, velocity, and position.<br /><br /><a href="http://cthulhu32.kraln.com/nesdev/physics/physics.0.1.nes" class="postlink">http://cthulhu32.kraln.com/nesdev/physics/physics.0.1.nes</a><br /><br />Press B to shoot the velocity up to max (it will wrap around and pop up on the top, didn't bother to add ceiling code). Also, if you wait a minute,  you'll notice the velocity gets smaller and smaller till the mario eventually stops moving.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3905">Cthulhu32</a> — Wed May 13, 2009 7:40 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
